<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-07-11T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-07-11T16:00:00-05:00" n="537" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">121.893/7–1147: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-07-11T17:00:00-04:00">July 11,
                                1947—5 p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>857. The President of the United States desires to send General Wedemeyer and
                        a small group of assistants to make a fact-findinsr appraisal of the current
                        and projected situation in China and Korea. General Wedemeyer will leave
                        almost immediately and the duration of his mission is estimated at 1 month
                        to 6 weeks.</p>
                    <p>Please see the Generalissimo<note n="12a" xml:id="d537fn1">Chiang Kai-shek,
                            President of the Nationalist Government of the Republic of China.</note>
                        as soon as practical and deliver the above message.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>